While + Past Continuous

We often use while + past continuous to describe a new action that happened in the middle of an action that was in progress in the past.
We use the simple past tense in the main cause and the past continuous in the clause with while.

I saw her while I was shopping. 
(Shopping was in progress when I saw her)

We met while I was living in Paris.

I fell asleep while I was watching the movie.

What did you do while you were waiting?

I read my emails while I was waiting.

